    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.0a-0d_0001-4"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <note type="curatorial">1931, 2, 3?</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">0a</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear Mr Neihardt
                    (Flaming Rainbow)</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>What a shrine of beauty your heart is, and how the fragrance of your soul responds to the slightest zephyr of the spirit.</p>
                
                <p>Now can I tell you what your beautiful letter meant to me, it made the day a holiday of the soul.</p> 
                
                <p>I so appreciate what you say about time, with you one of the reasons is, "where loving hearts are, time is not."</p>
                
                <p>I knew your wife was an <unclear>exquisite</unclear> spirit, one felt it in your dedication <unclear>poems</unclear> to the flowering of your love &#8212;
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.0a-0d_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">0b</fw>
                
                    your dear children.</p>
                
                <p>What a blessed thing to have real inner companionship. We too are so blessed, been adventuring together our thirty-eight happy years, filled with golden memories.</p>
                
                <p>We have no children of our own, but Mr <unclear>Hoelman's</unclear> work is among young people he teaches and lectures at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts.</p> 
                
                <p>No, you didn't mention before that you were working on &#8212; The Song of The Messiah.</p>
                
                <p>After reading the glad tidings, I seemed bathed in light.
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.0a-0d_0003"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">0c</fw>
                
                    I walked over to a little shrine, with its picture of the Shepherd of The <unclear>Lonely. and Healer</unclear> of Souls He looks like a spiritual white flame in which he seemed to beg you to be a channel of His Love and Compassion to man.</p>
                
                <p>And then suddenly one of the <unclear>beats</unclear> of life was mine when God lets you momentarily see with His Eyes.</p>
                
                <p>In the picture His Hand is pointing to His Heart, and I heard with The inner voice that is so compelling and stirring and beautiful, that you were writing The Song right out of this heart, and I knew your choice was 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.0a-0d_0004"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">0d</fw>
                
                    preordained, yea, <unclear>verily</unclear>, "There was a man sent from God, whose name is John."</p>
                
                <p>'Would I care to have your collected poems?' Oh, <unclear>Poet</unclear> Man, I hold out my hands <unclear>reverently</unclear> to receive your <unclear>poems</unclear>, they will indeed be a precious gift to me!</p> 
                
                <p>Last week, on his birthday, we held goblets on high, and drank to the <unclear>true</unclear> of <unclear>our</unclear> appreciation of John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt.!</p>
                
                <p><unclear>Go</unclear> forth I feel your broad humanity and understandably as a man.</p>
                
                <p>With the warmest wishes of our hearts to you and your dear family.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely</salute>
                    
                    <signed><unclear>Minnie Adelman</unclear></signed>
                
                    <dateline>Jan. 16th 33.</dateline>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
